DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
This domain examines German and European housing policy including rent control (Mietpreisbremse),
social housing decline, housing benefits (Wohngeld), and institutional arrangements. Germany's
unique context: extensive rental sector (54% renters), declining social housing (from 4 million
1980s to 1 million today), tenant protections, and 2015 rent control introduction. Key findings:
Mietpreisbremse showed limited effectiveness (initial 5% rent reduction disappeared within year).
Social housing decline due to subsidy elimination and privatization. Wohngeld effective in
reducing burden for recipients but limited reach. Housing policy interventions have modest effects
on burden distribution, suggesting structural factors (wages, housing supply) more determinative.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
Provides institutional context for understanding housing burden variation. Tests effectiveness of
policy interventions. Shows limits of housing-side policies when wage-side (H3, H4) and structural
factors (H5) dominant.

KEY_DEBATES:
- Effectiveness of rent control vs. supply-side policies
- Social housing decline and privatization effects
- Targeting efficiency of housing benefits
- Tenant protection vs. housing supply trade-offs
====================================================================
